Mr. Gronlund, for example, conceiving of the State as strictly an organism, and actually related to its citizens as a tree to its cells, denies that individuale have any

. But this is done not by putting duty in the fore·

ground; it is done by obliterating duty, and sub- stituting sor it servility. What is got rid of is morality altogether, alike in the form of duty and of right.

Other Socialists reach a similar result by investing the will of the majority with absolute authority in the moral sphere. It is interesting to note, how- ever, that those who prefer this course consider that the will of the majority is only to be thus revered as the source and law of right and duty when it has adopted a socialistic creed.
